commitResults.messageTitle: Extend add command to support new categories
commitResults.messageBody:
The add command only supports editing a small subset of a contact's details (name, phone, email, address).

Our target audience (financial advisors) would want more critical attributes of each client.

Let's,
* expand AddCommandParser to recognise prefixes for salary, date of birth, marital status, dependents, occupation
* update the AddCommand logic to apply these changes to a Person
* enhance the UI to correctly display these newly editable fields

commitResults.messageTitle: Extend edit command to support new categories
commitResults.messageBody:
The edit command only supports editing a small subset of a person's details (name, phone, email, address).

Our target audience (financial advisors) would want more critical attributes of each client.

Let's,
* expand EditCommandParser to recognise prefixes for salary, date of birth, marital status, dependents, occupation
* update the EditCommand logic to apply these changes to a Person
* enhance the UI to correctly display these newly editable fields, including formatted currency for salary.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update add and edit commands with InsurancePackage prefix
commitResults.messageBody:
The Person model now includes a compulsory InsurancePackage field. The
add and edit commands currently do not support this new field,
preventing users from adding or modifying this essential information.

Update both AddCommandParser and EditCommandParser to recognize and
parse the new ip/ prefix.

This ensures that user commands are consistent with the updated Person
model and allows for full data manipulation.

The application does not provide a way for users to modify an insurance
package's description after its creation. To change a description, a
user must delete the existing package and create a new one with the
updated details.

This process is inefficient for minor changes, such as correcting typos
or updating policy information. A direct editing function helps with
effective data management and improves the user experience.

Let's,

* Introduce a new editp command to modify the description of an existing
 insurance package.
* Implement the corresponding command parser and execution logic.
* Restrict the command to only modify the description, leaving the
package name unchanged.

The package name serves as the unique identifier for an insurance
package and is used for equality checks and associations with clients.
Making the name immutable via this command prevents data integrity
issues. The scope is intentionally limited to the description, which is
the safest attribute to modify.

Make various categories optional in add command
commitResults.messageBody:
The add command requires all person attributes (e.g., Salary,
Occupation, Dependents) to be provided.

This is inflexible and leads to poor usability since a user may not
have all this information when creating a new contact.

Let's,
* make Salary, DateOfBirth, MaritalStatus, Occupation, and Dependents
optional in the add command.
* update AddCommandParser to only validate the presence of required
fields (Name, Phone, Email, Address, InsurancePackage).
* modify optional attribute classes (Salary, DateOfBirth, etc.) to
support an "Unspecified" state. The Dependents class now uses -1 as its
internal "Unspecified" value.

The parser initializes these optional fields to their "Unspecified"
default, only overwriting them if the user provides the prefix or edits
them using the edit command.

The parser finds all known prefixes in an input string even when a
prefix is inside the value of another field. This prevents users from
entering names with text resembling a prefix and creates a poor user
experience. Moreover, only alphanumerical characters are allowed which
is overly restrictive for certain names that contain hyphens or
apostrophes.

Let's:
* expand the regex to allow Unicode and a set of special
non-alphanumerical characters that are commonly found in names
* allow users to enclose names with prefixes with one set of double
quotes
* capitalize letters following any of these new special characters for
better formatting

Making the tokenizer quote-aware is the most robust solution to this
problem, because it allows the Name field to be fully flexible without
requiring users to avoid certain characters.

A small side effect that results from this consistent naming standard
is that names with multiple capitalised letters will only have their
first letter capitalised.
